class Solution {
public:
    string strWithout3a3b(int a, int b) {
        string result = "";
        while (a > 0 || b > 0) {
            if (a > b) {
                if (a >= 2 && b > 0) {
                    result += "aab";
                    a -= 2;
                    b -= 1;
                } else {
                    result += "a";
                    a -= 1;
                }
            } else {
                if (b >= 2 && a > 0) {
                    result += "bba";
                    b -= 2;
                    a -= 1;
                } else {
                    result += "b";
                    b -= 1;
                }
            }
        }
        return result;
    }
};
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(a + b)
space complexity: O(a + b)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: The solution constructs the string by alternating between 'a' and 'b' while ensuring that neither 'aaa' nor 'bbb' occurs. It prioritizes the character with the higher count, appending it twice if possible, and then appends the other character. This greedy approach efficiently generates a valid string.
